In a text book it is stated that it can be proved using Gronwall's Lemma that the solution of the following problem depends continuously on initial data. However I could not make use of Gronwall's Lemma. $$x'(t) + 2x(t) -y(t) = \sin{(y(t))}$$ $$y'(t)+y(t)-x(t) = \cos{(x(t))}$$ $$x(0) = x_0, \quad y(0) = y_0$$ Any kind of help will be very useful! edit: Gronwall's lemma: Suppose that $u(t),v(t)$ are non-negative, continuous funcitons on $[0,T),$ $c \geq 0$ and $$\mbox{}u(t)\leq c + {\int_{0}^t u(s)v(s)d(s)}$$ Then, $$
\mbox{u}(t) \leq c * e^{\int_{0}^t v(s)d(s)} 
$$ $\forall t \in [0,T)$

